<HEADLINE>
<P>
WEST VALLEY FOCUS: CHATSWORTH; CHARITY EVENT IS AS EASY AS PIE FOR DEVON 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By JEANNETTE REGALADO 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Top executives of Devon Industries on Friday couldn't escape being targets of 
their employees' sweet revenge. 
</P>
<P>
 At $1 a throw, 276 employees of the Chatsworth medical supplies company lined 
up after lunch Friday to throw whipped creamed pies at the faces of Devon 
President Joseph R. Kletzel and a few of his vice presidents -- all in the name 
of charity.The pie-throwing event was held to raise money for the American 
Cancer Society's Making Strides walk-a-thon to be held June 4 at CityWalk in 
Universal City. 
</P>
<P>
 "They stuck their heads through big plastic sheets but it didn't help much," 
said Jim Wunderlich, spokesman for the company. "The pies were just flying." 
</P>
<P>
 The executives took turns at being targets. Mike Griffin, vice president of 
operations, spent the longest time as a target. He withstood the sticky 
onslaught for 20 minutes. 
</P>
<P>
 "The truth is most of these pies weren't thrown," Wunderlich said. "People 
walked right up to them and smashed it into their faces." 
</P>
<P>
 Wunderlich said at times, a whole department would gang up on their boss and 
throw the pies all at once, "really slamming the victim." 
</P>
<P>
 "But it was a good time for everyone," he said with a laugh. JEANNETTE 
REGALADO 
</P>
