<HEADLINE>
<P>
COUNTYWIDE FOCUS: STORM BLAMED FOR FATAL CRASH AND MUDSLIDES 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By TRACY WILSON 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 A slow-moving Pacific storm that contributed to a fatal car accident and 
caused minor mudslides and traffic tie-ups Friday is expected to hover over 
Ventura County throughout the weekend, producing scattered showers and a chance 
of thunderstorms, forecasters said. 
</P>
<P>
 During a 30-minute period Friday afternoon, the California Highway Patrol 
reported half a dozen traffic accidents in the Ventura County area, including 
an accident that killed two people near Bates Road just north of the county 
line.  
</P>
<P>
 Two died and four others were critically injured when three cars were involved 
in a head-on crash on the southbound Ventura Freeway at about 3 p.m., the CHP 
said. One of the cars hydroplaned, jumped the center divider and crashed into 
oncoming traffic, the CHP said. 
</P>
<P>
 One of the dead was identified as Jonathan Jenkins, 32, a resident of England, 
the CHP said. The identity of the other person killed, a Santa Barbara 
resident, was not released.  
</P>
<P>
 The four survivors, whose identities were not available late Friday, were all 
in critical condition at St. Francis Medical Center in Santa Barbara, 
authorities said. 
</P>
<P>
 Southbound lanes of the freeway were closed and traffic rerouted to California 
150 for several hours, the CHP said. 
</P>
<P>
 Caltrans workers responded to mudslides at three locations on the Pacific 
Coast Highway, but kept the road open.  
</P>
<P>
 Organizers of the Ventura Police Department's Block Party and the Hispanic 
Chamber of Commerce's Cinco de Mayo festival in Oxnard said today's events will 
proceed as scheduled. County Rainfall 
</P>
<P>
 Here are rainfall figures from the Ventura County Flood Control District for 
the 24-hour period ending 5 p.m. Friday. Oct. 1 is the beginning of the 
official rain year. 04,22,15,14,17 Rainfall Rainfall Normal rainfall Location 
