<HEADLINE>
<P>
RESEDA'S ARREOLA GETS PUNCHED OUT; HIGH SCHOOL BASEBALL: HE IS SUSPENDED FOR 
SEASON AFTER HITTING CHATSWORTH'S LACOUR DURING POSTGAME HANDSHAKE. 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By VINCE KOWALICK, TIMES STAFF WRITER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Maybe postgame handshakes aren't such a good idea after all. 
</P>
<P>
 As expected, Reseda High's Alonzo Arreola was suspended for the remainder of 
the season Friday for punching Chatsworth's Bryan LaCour in the stomach as the 
teams shook hands after a West Valley League baseball game Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
 Meanwhile, Jeff LaCour, whose son was not hurt in the incident, said he has 
dismissed the idea of filing charges against Arreola. 
</P>
<P>
 "It's over and done with," LaCour said. "The Chatsworth administration told me 
he would be suspended for the rest of the year. I'm satisfied with that." 
</P>
<P>
 The incident occurred just a few weeks after the debate over the exchange of 
postgame pleasantries made national headlines. 
</P>
<P>
 In March, a vote by Marmonte League administrators banned postgame handshakes 
because of the tendency for tempers to flare between players. 
</P>
<P>
 However, the ban was rescinded a few weeks later after coaches and 
administrators were bombarded with inquiries and criticism from media 
throughout the nation. 
</P>
<P>
 On Thursday, emotion ran high during Chatsworth's 7-2 victory. Moments after 
the final out, Arreola, a senior third baseman, caught LaCour by surprise. 
</P>
<P>
 "I suspended him on the bus on the way home," Reseda Coach Mike Stone said. "I 
talked to the whole team about it, including Alonzo. I made the decision before 
I talked to anyone at the school. I told the administration this morning what 
the decision was and they went along with it." 
</P>
<P>
 Stone said his players were the target of barbs from the Chatsworth bench 
throughout the game. Stone also said LaCour stepped on Arreola's toes when the 
players met at third base. 
</P>
<P>
 Immediately after the incident, LaCour's father said he would consider filing 
assault charges against Arreola. 
</P>
</TEXT>
