BOBBITT ACCUSED OF ASSAULT ON HIS ROOMMATE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Associated Press 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 John Wayne Bobbitt -- the man who gained international attention when his wife 
severed his penis -- was back in the headlines Friday, accused of roughing up a 
former topless dancer with whom he had been living. 
</P>
<P>
 Las Vegas police said Bobbitt appeared to be "under the influence of alcohol 
or other substance" when he grabbed Kristina Elliot by the arm and shoved her 
into a wall at their apartment. 
</P>
<P>
 The woman suffered bruises but did not require medical treatment, according to 
Aaron Gordon, a spokesman for the couple. 
</P>
<P>
 Gordon said the incident was "a misunderstanding that got blown out of 
proportion." He said Elliot, 21, was "more emotionally hurt than anything." 
</P>
<P>
 Asked if she planned to press charges against Bobbitt, Gordon said, "It's 
about 50-50." 
</P>
<P>
 Nevada law does not require the victim of domestic battery to pursue 
prosecution for an arrest to be made or charges filed. 
</P>
<P>
 A police report said the two were involved "in a verbal argument before 
Bobbitt grabbed her right forearm, causing a bruise, then shoved her into a 
wall, causing a bruise." 
</P>
<P>
 Police were required by Nevada law to hold Bobbitt for at least a 12-hour 
cooling-off period. 
