<HEADLINE>
<P>
YANKEE SCHEDULE GETS TOUGHER, STARTING WITH BOSTON 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By JON HEYMAN, NEWSDAY 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 So far, the Yankees' schedule has been a lot like the weather they've seen: 
mild and breezy. Things have been fairly fun in the sun out west, but now 
things get serious. The vacation is over. School's on. 
</P>
<P>
 The first-place Boston Red Sox are coming to town starting Friday night and 
they're off to their best start since 1946. So the Yankees finally will get a 
real idea about where they stand. After playing 23 of 26 games against losing 
teams, the Yankees are looking at a real test, a real team. 
</P>
<P>
 Even if these new-style, low-key Yankees can't work up any legitimate hatred 
for the Red Sox (not even ex-Red Sox Wade Boggs can), they do understand it is 
different facing Roger Clemens than Miguel Jimenez. The Yankees and Red Sox 
both conquered the West (the Red Sox squashed it, going 13-2, including 11-0 
against California and Oakland), but now they'll find out how they stack up 
against each other, which is all that really matters anyway. 
</P>
<P>
 Yankees ace Jimmy Key, who starts Friday night against right-hander Aaron 
Sele, in his usual no-frills, no-bull manner, said about the Red Sox, "They're 
playing as good or better than anybody in baseball. ... They're one of the 
teams we have to beat if we're going to win our division. We don't want to put 
a lot of emphasis on winning all three games, but we want to play well to show 
them we can hang with them." 
</P>
<P>
 The Yankees can't be certain what to expect this weekend, even from 
themselves. Twenty-six games in, their only winning opponent, the White Sox, 
beat them two out of three. Yes, they are 16-10, but it's a fairly hollow 
16-10. 
</P>
<P>
 The Yankees aren't overwhelming anyone, even themselves. They're biggest 
weapon so far has been the walk. They're on pace to walk 897 times, which 
amounts to 15.4 miles of walking. There has been little to become enthused 
about. "I don't think we've played as well as we're going to or are capable of 
playing. I think we're capable of better," Manager Buck Showalter said. 
</P>
<P>
 Among the questions they took into the season, these remain unanswered: Can 
they depend upon the bullpen? Will Jim Abbott and Melido Perez pitch to their 
ample abilities? Is Luis Polonia the leadoff answer? And can Mike Stanley, Mike 
Gallego, Paul O'Neill, Jim Leyritz and Randy Velarde repeat breakthrough 
seasons? 
</P>
<P>
 -- The bullpen is looking a little leaky lately. Jeff Reardon blew Abbott's 
5-2 lead in their 7-6, 13-inning defeat to the California Angels late Wednesday 
night, capping a bad trip for the pen, which lost Steve Howe to injury and 
surrendered one big hit almost nightly. 
</P>
<P>
 -- People are making a fuss over Abbott's low radar-gun readings (opponents 
say he's in the 85-86-mph range), but he's still 3-2 with a 2.87 ERA so he's 
compensating with better pitching. Perez looks better after shoulder surgery, 
and now the question is whether the toe he injured by angrily kicking a 
Gatorade container will affect his start tomorrow. 
</P>
<P>
 -- If there's a problem with Polonia, it's his base-running. Polonia, batting 
.280 at the plate and about that on the bases, said, "I always took risks, but 
for some reason it isn't working now. It's been bad all the time, there hasn't 
been one time I went and was successful. Eight times I've screwed up on the 
bases, somebody got a base hit right after that. I know, I'm counting, one by 
one." 
</P>
<P>
 -- Among those trying to repeat huge seasons, O'Neill (.446), Velarde (.321) 
and Leyritz (.357) are actually doing even better. But Gallego (.216) and 
Stanley (.190) can't see where they were last season with a telescope. 
</P>
<P>
 Perhaps the Yankees will start getting some more definitive answers to their 
mostly unanswered questions beginning Friday night, when the real tests begin. 
</P>
</TEXT>
